###### 3.3 [Fermat's Little Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_little_theorem)

*If $p$ is a prime number and $a$ is any positive integer less than $p$, then $a$ raised to the $p$th power is congruent to $a$ modulo $p$* (SICP, 1996; [2016, p.67](https://web.mit.edu/6.001/6.037/sicp.pdf)):

$\boxed{\text{If } isprime(p) \text{ then } \forall a \in \{a|1 < a < p\}: a^p \equiv a\ (\bmod p)}.$

Another form can be obtained by dividing both sides of the equivalence by $a$:

$\boxed{\text{If } isprime(p) \text{ then } \forall a \in \{a|1 < a < p\}: a^{p-1} \equiv 1\ (\bmod p)}.$

where $\{a|1 < a < p\} \in \mathbb N$ is called *basis* and where:

$a^n \equiv a\ (\bmod n) \text{ is an abbreviation for: } a^n\ (\bmod n) = a\ (\bmod n).$

*Two numbers are said to be congruent modulo n if they both have the same remainder when divided by n. The remainder of a number a when divided by n is also referred to as the 'remainder of a modulo n', or simply as 'a modulo n'.* (SICP)

We can summarize *Fermat's Little Theorem* (CLRS, 2022, ch. 31.8, p.944):

$\boxed{P(test\ |\ nature) = P\left(\forall a | a \in \mathbb Z^+_n: a^{n-1} = 1\ (mod\  n)\;|\;isprime(n)\right) = 1\ }$

and the *inverse diagnostic* rule

$\boxed{P(nature\ |\ test) = P\left(isprime(n) \;|\; \forall a | a \in \mathbb Z^+_n: a^{n-1} = 1\ (mod\  n)\right) < 1\ }.$
"

# ╔═╡ 6bf2767d-5822-478e-83d5-6e196435aadd
md"
This is compatible with the following 

###### *Confusion matrix*:

$\begin{array}{l|cc|c}
Test \text{ \\ } Nature  & prime   & composite & sum     \\
\hline
FermatTest = prime       &   TP    &    FP     & TP + FP \\
FermatTest = composite   & FN = 0  &    TN     &   TN    \\
\hline
sum                      &   TP    &  FP + TN  &   N     \\
\end{array}$

###### *Causal* direction

$P(FTest=prime|Nature=prime) = \frac{TP}{TP+0} = 1\;;\text{ perfect sensivity, recall}$
$P(FTest=composite|Nature=prime) = \frac{0}{TP+0} = 0\;;\text{ perfect sensivity}$
$P(FTest=prime|Nature=composite) = \frac{FP}{FP+TN} < 1\;;\text{ Carmichael numbers }$
$P(FTest=composite|Nature=composite) = \frac{TN}{FP+TN} < 1$

###### *Diagnostic* direction

$P(Nature=prime|FTest=prime) = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} < 1\;;\text{ precision }$
$P(Nature=composite|FTest=prime) = \frac{TP}{TP+FP} < 1\;;\text{ precision, Carmichael }$
$P(Nature=prime|FTest=composite) = \frac{0}{TN} = 0$
$P(Nature=composite|FTest=composite) = \frac{TN}{TN} = 1.$

with:
- TP = frequency of *true positives*
- FP = frequency of *false positives*
- TN = frequency of *true negatives*
- FN = frequency of *false negatives*
"

