###### 3.3.1 *Modular-Exponentiation* $expmod$

*To implement the Fermat test, we need a procedure that computes
the exponential of a number modulo another number* (SICP, 1996; 2016, p.67; Cormen, 2022, ch. 31.6, p.935):

$a^b \bmod n =
\begin{cases}
1,  & \text{ if } b = 0  \\
\left(a^{(b/2)}\right)^2 \;\bmod n,  & \text{ if } (b > 0) \land iseven(b)\\
b * a^{(b-1)} \bmod n,  & \text{ if } (b > 0) \land isodd(b)  \\
\end{cases}.$

"

# ╔═╡ 99f32ce2-e7c5-4a0a-b466-d7ecf5ef6af4
md"
... with *self-defined* type $FloatOrInteger.$ The same function is implemented in *Julia* under the name $powermod(base, exp, n).$
"

# ╔═╡ 8bbdd3d4-9a2b-478d-8ba4-7ca3a10aa86e
FloatOrSigned = Union{AbstractFloat, Signed}

# ╔═╡ 0af40eda-a6fd-4fb3-9d77-129c02d66b79
function expmod(base::Signed, exp::FloatOrSigned, n::Signed)
	#---------------------------------------------------------
	exp == 0    ? 1 :
	iseven(exp) ? expmod(base, exp / 2, n)^2 % n :
		   base * expmod(base, exp - 1, n) % n
end # function expmod

# ╔═╡ bff175b8-7637-40ae-84a5-3047a5c71d30
md"
---
$2^3\ \equiv 2\ (\bmod 3) = 2 \text{ is same as: }  2^3\ (\bmod 3) \equiv 2\ (\bmod 3) = 2$
"

