# ╔═╡ f3e9ad78-79f2-4aeb-8113-c8f50d05e68e
md"
---
###### 3.4 [Fermat's Little Theorem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fermat%27s_little_theorem) (short version, e.g. Cormen et al., 2022, p.932)

If *basis* $a$ and *test candidate* $p$ are *coprime* then $gcd(a, p)==1$. In this case we can divide both sides of the equivalence 

$a^p\ (\bmod p) \equiv a\ (\bmod p)$ 

by $a\ (\bmod p)$. Now, we get:

$a^{p-1}\ (\bmod p) \equiv a^{1-1}\ (\bmod p) = a^0\ (\bmod p) = 1\ (\bmod p) = 1.$

So:

$a^{p-1}\ (\bmod p) = 1.$

We can include the condition $gcd(p, a) = 1$ as a precondition in *Fermat*'s test. If we *know* that $isprime(p)$ is *true* this check is redundant. In other cases we can use it as a *quick-check*. If $gcd(p, a) > 1$ then we know that $isprime(p)$ is *false* and $p$ is *composite*. Otherwise we are *uncertain* whether $p$ is *prime* or *pseudoprime* (=*Carmichael*) and we have to go on with testing.

Now we can write the *short* version of *Fermat's Little Theorem* as:

$\boxed{P(test\ |\ nature) = 1}$
$\boxed{= P\left(\forall a | a \in \mathbb Z^+_n: (gcd(p, a) = 1) \land (a^{n-1} = 1\ (mod\  n))\;|\;isprime(n)\right) = 1\ }$

and the *inverse diagnostic* rule

$\boxed{P(nature\ |\ test) < 1\ }$
$\boxed{= P\left(isprime(n) \;|\; \forall a | a \in \mathbb Z^+_n: (gcd(p, a) = 1) \land (a^{n-1} = 1\ (mod\  n))\right) < 1\ }.$

"

