##### 5. Summary
We presented *exhaustive* and *nonexhaustive, probabilistic* search methods for identifying *primenes* of natural numbers. The results are assembled in the following table. For production purposes the *library* function $isprime(.)$ is recommended.

$\begin{array}{l|cccr|c}
\text{function} & \text{trial division} & \text{replication} & \text{Carmichael} & \text{trials} & \text{complexity} \\
\hline
isPrime     & exhaustive    & tail-recurs. & not\ fooled     & >   1 & \Theta(\sqrt n) \\
isPrime2    & exhaustive    & tail-recurs. & not\ fooled     & >   1 & \Theta(\sqrt n) \\
isPrime3    & exhaustive    & iterative    & not\ fooled     & >   1 & \Theta(\sqrt n) \\
isPrime4    & exhaustive    & iterative    & not\ fooled     & >   1 & \Theta(\sqrt n) \\
\hline
fermatTest1 & probabilistic & tail-recurs. & fooled          & =   1 & \Theta((\log n)^3) \\ 
fastPrime1  & probabilistic & tail-recurs. & fooled          & = 100 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
fermatTest2 & probabilistic & tail-recurs. & fooled\ (p≈.81) & =   1 & \Theta((\log n)^3) \\
fastPrime2  & probabilistic & tail-recurs. & not\ fooled     & =  10 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
fastPrime3  & probabilistic & iterative    & fooled\ (p≈.06) & =  10 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
fastPrime3  & probabilistic & iterative    & not\ fooled     & =  20 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
millerRabin & probabilistic & recursive    & fooled\ (p≈.06) & =  10 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
millerRabin & probabilistic & recursive    & not\ fooled     & =  20 & \Theta(k(\log n)^3) \\
isprime     & probabilistic & iterative    & not\ fooled     & =   1 & \Theta(\log n)^3 \\
\hline
\end{array}$

